author: Darren Boyle for MailOnline
title: Sea lion eats Thresher shark off Californian coast
text:
Call yourself Jaws! Breath taking images show a hungry sea lion eating an eight-foot-long SHARK in a dinner time death duel By Darren Boyle for MailOnline
Published: 14:23 GMT, 31 January 2017 | Updated: 15:19 GMT, 31 January 2017
© Dale Frink / mediadrumworld.com © Dale Frink / mediadrumworld.com This is the amazing moment a sea lion bites the head off an eight-foot-long Thresher shark off the Californian coast
© Dale Frink / mediadrumworld.com The sea lion easily defeated the shark according to pictures captured by wildlife photographer Dale Frink
© Dale Frink / mediadrumworld.com The sea lion tossed the shark around in the air despite having already removed its head and killing it
The drama took place off Newport Beach, California The images were captured by photographer Dale Frink The 660-pound sea lion easily defeated the shark Thresher sharks use their tails to stun their prey © Dale Frink / mediadrumworld.com The 660-pound shark bit lumps out of the shark while continuing to play with his victim
© Dale Frink / mediadrumworld.com The unbelievable scenes were captured off the coast of Newport Beach in California by photographer Dale Frink
© Dale Frink / mediadrumworld.com The sea lion devoured the eight-foot-long shark without encountering any serious problems
© Dale Frink / mediadrumworld.com At one stage it appeared the shark broke free from the sea lion's grip - but it wasn't going far without its head
© Dale Frink / mediadrumworld.com The Thresher shark uses his large tail to stun his victims before trying to eat them although he was match for the sea lion
© Dale Frink / mediadrumworld.com The Thresher shark does not really pose a threat to humans although there have been reports of people hit by its tail
© Dale Frink / mediadrumworld.com Sports fisherman are a major threat to the Thresher shark as are hunters looking to harvest its liver oil and skin
© Dale Frink / mediadrumworld.com The Thresher shark is known to target mackerel, small tuna and occasionally, an unsuspecting sea bird
© Dale Frink / mediadrumworld.com The sea lion, pictured, looked rather content having defeated the Thresher shark in the dinner time death duel
